line_1: Only this I now discern
line_2: From the things, thou'd'st have me learn,

line_1: His real interest to discern?
line_2: Will Man but by experience learn?

line_1: Alone can all my wants discern,
line_2: Author of good! to thee I turn;

line_1: While, by the ling'ring light, I scarce discern
line_2: O'er the tall brow of yonder chalky bourn,

line_1: This Axiom clearly I discern,
line_2: That One must Teach, and t'Other Learn.

line_1: Nor carp at ev'ry flaw you may discern,
line_2: Oh thwart me not, Sir Soph. at ev'ry turn,

line_1: Till, soaring higher, striving to discern
line_2: Her hidden Fate, and future Fortune learn,

line_1: My path I could hardly discern;
line_2: I thought that she bade me return.

line_1: In moles and specks we Fortune's gifts discern,
line_2: And Fate's fix'd will from Nature's wanderings learn.

line_1: Where weak-ey'd Reason's self may well discern
line_2: What joy for tutor'd Piety to learn,

line_1: More prone to doubt, than anxious to discern:
line_2: Curious of knowing, yet too proud to learn;

line_2: Let me, forewarn'd, each Sign, each System learn,

line_2: Judge his own ways, and sigh for a return,

line_2: I reckon Covent-garden church a barn.
